  "prompt": "What's the difference between shares and stocks?",
  "response": "While the terms \"shares\" and \"stocks\" are often used interchangeably, there is a subtle difference between them:\n\nStocks:\n- A broader term representing ownership in a company\n- Represents a type of financial security\n- Signifies equity ownership in a corporation\n\nShares:\n- A specific unit of stock\n- Represents the smallest denomination of a company's stock\n- Indicates the number of equity units owned in a particular company\n\nFor example:\n- You might say \"I own stock in Apple\" (general term)\n- You could also say \"I own 100 shares of Apple\" (specific quantity)\n\nIn practical usage, most people use these terms synonymously, and the difference is often minimal in everyday conversation. The key point is that both represent ownership in a company.",
